Notes: Standard meta analyses requires that tests be independent (i.e., only one ES per study)

For negative affect. Will include a composite score. But then just conduct ES for each variable tested and then separate MA for each variable.

Vansteelandt et al., 2017

van<-read.csv("/Users/kevinkuehn/Documents/Writing/Kuehn et al. Psych Bull/NA-SITB_meta/Data/2020 data meta analysis Vansteelandt.csv")

mean(van$NA., na.rm=T)

## [1] 27.84431

Effect size calculation

NSSI behaviors

vars<-c("NA.standard", "NSSI")
NA.NSSI<-van[vars]
s<-pooled.sd(NA.NSSI)

Antecedent model (comparing affect pre NSSI to affect pre non-NSSI observation)

a<-mean(van[van$NSSI.pre==1,"NA.standard"], na.rm=T)

b<-mean(van[van$NSSI.pre==0,"NA.standard"], na.rm=T)

c<-a-b
d<-c/s
d
## [1] 0.9771299

Effect size for antecedent model 0.9771299

This suggests that NA was 0.9771299 higher at report prior to NSSI compared to non-NSSI

a.2<-van$NA.standard[van$NSSI.pre==1]
b.2<-van$NA.standard[van$NSSI.pre==0]
b.3<-sample(b.2, length(a.2))
cor(a.2,b.3, use="pairwise.complete.obs")
## [1] -0.08621284

Consequence model: comparing affect prior to NSSI to affect post NSSI

e<-mean(van[van$NSSI,"NA.standard"], na.rm=TRUE)

f<-e-a
g<-f/s

Effect size for consequence model is -0.5438619

This suggests that NA was .54 SD units lower following NSSI compared to pre NSSI NA.

a.4<-van$NA.standard[van$NSSI.pre==1]
b.4<-van$NA.standard[van$NSSI==1]
a.5<-sample(a.4, size=length(b.4))
cor(a.5,b.4, use="pairwise.complete.obs")
## [1] -0.3164085

Bresin et al., 2013

Effect size calculation

NSSI thoughts

vars<-c("NA.standard", "NSSI")
NA.NSSI<-bres[vars]
s<-pooled.sd(NA.NSSI)

Antecedent model (comparing affect pre NSSI to affect pre non-NSSI observation)

a<-mean(bres[bres$NSSI.pre==1,"NA.standard"], na.rm=T)
b<-mean(bres[bres$NSSI.pre==0,"NA.standard"], na.rm=T)

c<-a-b
c/s
## [1] 0.4250283

Effect size for antecedent model is 0.4250283

This suggests that NA was .43 SD units higher on average prior to NSSI thoughts

Consequence model: comparing affect prior to NSSI to affect post NSSI

d<-mean(bres[bres$NSSI.post==1,"NA.standard"], na.rm=TRUE)

e<-d-a
f<-e/s

Effect size for consequence model is 0.025143

This suggests that NA was .025 SD units higher following NSSI compared to pre NSSI NA.

Calculate observation number and suicidal thoughts variable

evans<-evans[!(evans$ID.1 %in% c(33, NA)), ]

Effect size calculation

Suicidal thoughts
